The data was approximately 30,000 labeled and 20,000 unlabeled images of plankton, classified into 121 different species. Immediate problems were the unbalanced distribution of classes shown in figure 2 and the varying sizes of the images, shown in figure 3.
Data Augmentation

Augmenting the data was used for regularisation when training. The full selection applied, at different times included: Rotation (0-360 uniform), Reflection (Bernoulli), Translation (Gaussian in x and y), Scale (Gaussian), Stretch (Gaussian in x and y), Shear (Gaussian). Examples of the potentially infinite augmented images are shown in Figure 4.
Figure 4: examples of augmented images drawn from an infinite stream.
Model: Convolutional Neural Networks

For image classification tasks, convolutional networks are the state of the art. Our initial structure was based on the succesful AlexNet design. After experimenting with many proposed changes, including siamese networks, deeper networks and pooling strategies the final network with the best performance had only an extra convolutional layer. This structure is shown in figure 5.

Supplying the network features derived from heuristics in computer vision was expected to push the performance of the network past that of other teams. Unfortunately, this was not the case, and the network performed better without. The winning team, however, did integrate these features into their network succesfully.
Features used included: Haralick features, Grey-level co-occurence, Contour moments, Hu moments, Grey-level intensity histogram, Parameter-free threshold adjacency statistics, ORB, BRISK and MSER.
Figure 5: structure of the network used that produced the best performance.
Class Hierarchy

The classes have an intrinsic hierarchy which could be useful to improve training speed, and the information in error signals. Using the different levels in figure 6 a series of 1-of-k vectors could be created to supply to six softmax output layers in parallel.
Figure 6: Class hierarchy used for enecoding the classes to create a hierarchical targets.

Output: Results

An ensemble of three networks, two with the same architecture but different training schedules and one hierarchically trained model with a different architectrure were used to make the predictions that produced the best submission. The weighted average was estimated by stochastic gradient descent in the same manner as the models were trained, but performed on our holdout set.

Figure 7 shows the network correctly classifying an example image, showing the activations in various layers to demonstrate the effects of the different kernels learned. It is also able to classify the plankton into the correct superclasses, as shown on the right.
Figure 7: example activations and classification of a plankton image by the hierarchically trained convolutional network.
Leaderboard

The final score achieved on the private test set held by Kaggle was 0.704 log loss. The final ranking was 57th on the leaderboard as shown in figure 8 as a red line. Also shown are the score of the winning team in green and the class prior benchmark in grey.
Figure 8: log loss distribution on the leaderboard.
Conclusions

The ideas that were attempted were very similar to those used by the winning team, with the exception of cyclic pooling. Significant problems were likely due to insufficient testing of code, time constraints and inexperience otherwise the score could likely have been much better.
